class Solution {
    public String mergeAlternately(String word1, String word2) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        int i = 0, j = 0;

        while (i < word1.length() && j < word2.length()) {
            sb.append(word1.charAt(i));
            sb.append(word2.charAt(j));
            i++; j++;
        }

        while (i < word1.length()) {
            sb.append(word1.charAt(i));
            i++;
        }

        while (j < word2.length()) {
            sb.append(word2.charAt(j));
            j++;
        }

        return sb.toString();
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(min(m, n)) where m and n are the lengths of word1 and word2 respectively
space complexity: O(n) where n is the length of the shorter string
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We use three pointers (i, j, and sb) to iterate through the strings word1 and word2. We alternate between appending characters from both strings to a StringBuilder object (sb). The time complexity is O(min(m, n)) because we stop iterating as soon as one of the strings runs out of characters. The space complexity is O(n) because we only use a StringBuilder object of size n. Energy implications are low because the algorithm is efficient and does not require any complex operations.

